# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: avionics-systems
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:avionics-systems/air-data-computer] An **air data computer** (**ADC**) or **central air data computer** (**CADC**) computes critical real-time flight data.
[src:avionics-systems/air-data-computer] It is an essential avionics component found in modern aircraft.
[src:avionics-systems/air-data-computer] This computer, rather than individual instruments, can determine the calibrated airspeed, Mach number, altitude, and altitude trend data from pressure and temperature inputs from an aircraft's pitot-static system.
[src:avionics-systems/air-data-computer] In some very high-speed aircraft such as the Space Shuttle, equivalent airspeed is calculated instead of calibrated airspeed.
[src:avionics-systems/air-data-computer] Air data computers usually also have an input of total air temperature.
[src:avionics-systems/air-data-computer] This enables the computation of static air temperature and true airspeed.
[src:avionics-systems/air-data-computer] In Airbus aircraft the air data computer is combined with attitude, heading and navigation sources in a single unit known as the Air Data Inertial Reference Unit (ADIRU) which has now been replaced by the Global Navigation Air Data Inertial Reference System (GNADIRS).
[src:avionics-systems/air-data-computer] As all information from the sensors is transmitted electrically, routing of pitot and static pressure lines through the aircraft and associated maintenance tasks is avoided.
[src:avionics-systems/air-data-computer] In simpler aircraft and helicopters, the air data computers, generally two in number, and smaller, lighter and simpler than an ADIRU, may be called air data units, although their internal computational power is still significant.
[src:avionics-systems/air-data-computer] They commonly have the pitot and static pressure inputs, as well as outside air temperature from a platinum resistance thermometer and may control heating of the pitot tube and static vent to prevent blockage due to ice.
[src:avionics-systems/air-data-computer] On simpler aircraft, there is usually not a fly-by-wire system, so the outputs are typically to the cockpit altimeters or display system, flight data recorder and autopilot system.
[src:avionics-systems/air-data-computer] Output interfaces typically are ARINC 429, Gillham or even IEEE 1394 (Firewire).
[src:avionics-systems/air-data-computer] The data provided may be true airspeed, pressure altitude, density altitude and Outside Air Temperature (OAT), but with no involvement in aircraft attitude or heading, as there are no gyroscopes or accelerometers fitted internally.
[src:avionics-systems/air-data-computer] These devices are usually autonomous and do not require pilot input, merely sending continuously updated data to the recipient systems while the aircraft is powered up.
[src:avionics-systems/air-data-computer] Some, like the Enhanced Software Configurable Air Data Unit (ESCADU) are software configurable to suit many different aircraft applications.
[src:avionics-systems/air-data-computer] Apart from commercial ADCs, there are available do-it-yourself, and open-source implementations.
[src:avionics-systems/air-data-computer] Electrical-mechanical air data computers were developed in the early 1950s to provide a central source of airspeed, altitude, and other signals to avionic systems that needed this data.
[src:avionics-systems/air-data-computer] A central air data computer avoided duplication of sensing equipment and could be more sophisticated and accurate.
[src:avionics-systems/air-data-computer] The first air data computer was built by Kollsman Instruments for the B-52 bomber.
[src:avionics-systems/air-data-computer] Bendix started producing a central air data computer in 1956 for use on US Air Force jet fighters.
[src:avionics-systems/air-data-computer] Garrett AiResearch developed early central air data computer systems that integrated pneumatic, electrical, and electronic components.
[src:avionics-systems/air-data-computer] The late 1960s saw the introduction of digital air data computers.
[src:avionics-systems/air-data-computer] In 1967, Garrett AiResearch's ILAAS air data computer was the first all-digital unit.
[src:avionics-systems/air-data-computer] The DC-10 used Honeywell's digital air data system in 1969 and the F-14 CADC used on the F-14 in 1970 used custom integrated circuits.
[src:avionics-systems/air-data-computer] From the late 1980s much of the USAF and USN aircraft fleets were retrofitted with the GEC Avionics Rochester-developed Standard Central Air Data Computer (SCADC).
[src:avionics-systems/air-data-computer] Aircraft fitted included the A-4 Skyhawk, A-6 Intruder, A-7 Corsair, C-5A/B Galaxy, EA-6B Prowler, F-111 Aardvark, F-4 Phantom, S-3 Viking, C-141 Starlifter, C-135 Stratolifter, C-2 Greyhound, and E-2 Hawkeye, for which the company received the Queen's Award for Technological Achievement.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] A conventional fixed-wing **aircraft flight control system** consists of flight control surfaces, the respective cockpit controls, connecting linkages, and the necessary operating mechanisms to control an aircraft's direction in flight.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] Aircraft engine controls are also considered flight controls as they change speed.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] The fundamentals of aircraft controls are explained in flight dynamics.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] This article centers on the operating mechanisms of the flight controls.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] The basic system in use on aircraft first appeared in a readily recognizable form as early as April 1908, on Louis Blériot's Blériot VIII pioneer-era monoplane design.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] The control yokes also vary greatly among aircraft.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] Centre sticks also vary between aircraft.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] Some are directly connected to the control surfaces using cables, others (fly-by-wire airplanes) have a computer in between which then controls the electrical actuators.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] Flight control has long been taught in such fashion for many decades, as popularized in ab initio instructional books such as the 1944 work Stick and Rudder.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] In some aircraft, the control surfaces are not manipulated with a linkage.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] In ultralight aircraft and motorized hang gliders, for example, there is no mechanism at all.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] Instead, the pilot just grabs the lifting surface by hand (using a rigid frame that hangs from its underside) and moves it.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] In addition to the primary flight controls for roll, pitch, and yaw, there are often secondary controls available to give the pilot finer control over flight or to ease the workload.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] Many aircraft have wing flaps, controlled by a switch or a mechanical lever or in some cases are fully automatic by computer control, which alter the shape of the wing for improved control at the slower speeds used for take-off and landing.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] Other secondary flight control systems may include slats, spoilers, air brakes and variable-sweep wings.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] Mechanical or manually operated flight control systems are the most basic method of controlling an aircraft.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] They were used in early aircraft and are currently used in small aircraft where the aerodynamic forces are not excessive.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] A manual flight control system uses a collection of mechanical parts such as pushrods, tension cables, pulleys, counterweights, and sometimes chains to transmit the forces applied to the cockpit controls directly to the control surfaces.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] Turnbuckles are often used to adjust control cable tension.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] The Cessna Skyhawk is a typical example of an aircraft that uses this type of system.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] Gust locks are often used on parked aircraft with mechanical systems to protect the control surfaces and linkages from damage from wind.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] Some aircraft have gust locks fitted as part of the control system.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] Increases in the control surface area, and the higher airspeeds required by faster aircraft resulted in higher aerodynamic loads on the flight control systems.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] As a result, the forces required to move them also become significantly larger.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] Consequently, complicated mechanical gearing arrangements were developed to extract maximum mechanical advantage in order to reduce the forces required from the pilots.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] This arrangement can be found on bigger or higher performance propeller aircraft such as the Fokker 50.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] Some mechanical flight control systems use servo tabs that provide aerodynamic assistance.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] Servo tabs are small surfaces hinged to the control surfaces.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] The flight control mechanisms move these tabs, aerodynamic forces in turn move, or assist the movement of the control surfaces reducing the amount of mechanical forces needed.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] This arrangement was used in early piston-engined transport aircraft and in early jet transports.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] The Boeing 737 incorporates a system, whereby in the unlikely event of total hydraulic system failure, it automatically and seamlessly reverts to being controlled via servo-tab.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] The complexity and weight of mechanical flight control systems increase considerably with the size and performance of the aircraft.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] Hydraulically powered control surfaces help to overcome these limitations.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] With hydraulic flight control systems, the aircraft's size and performance are limited by economics rather than a pilot's muscular strength.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] At first, only-partially boosted systems were used in which the pilot could still feel some of the aerodynamic loads on the control surfaces (feedback).
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] The pilot's movement of a control causes the mechanical circuit to open the matching servo valve in the hydraulic circuit.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] The hydraulic circuit powers the actuators which then move the control surfaces.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] As the actuator moves, the servo valve is closed by a mechanical feedback linkage - one that stops movement of the control surface at the desired position.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] This arrangement was found in the older-designed jet transports and in some high-performance aircraft.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] Examples include the Antonov An-225 and the Lockheed SR-71.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] With purely mechanical flight control systems, the aerodynamic forces on the control surfaces are transmitted through the mechanisms and are felt directly by the pilot, allowing tactile feedback of airspeed.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] With hydromechanical flight control systems, the load on the surfaces cannot be felt and there is a risk of overstressing the aircraft through excessive control surface movement.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] To overcome this problem, artificial feel systems can be used.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] For example, for the controls of the RAF's Avro Vulcan jet bomber and the RCAF's Avro Canada CF-105 Arrow supersonic interceptor (both 1950s-era designs), the required force feedback was achieved by a spring device.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] The fulcrum of this device was moved in proportion to the square of the air speed (for the elevators) to give increased resistance at higher speeds.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] For the controls of the American Vought F-8 Crusader and the LTV A-7 Corsair II warplanes, a 'bob-weight' was used in the pitch axis of the control stick, giving force feedback that was proportional to the airplane's normal acceleration.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] A stick shaker is a device that is attached to the control column in some hydraulic aircraft.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] It shakes the control column when the aircraft is approaching stall conditions.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] Some aircraft such as the McDonnell Douglas DC-10 are equipped with a back-up electrical power supply that can be activated to enable the stick shaker in case of hydraulic failure.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] In most current systems the power is provided to the control actuators by high-pressure hydraulic systems.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] In fly-by-wire systems the valves, which control these systems, are activated by electrical signals.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] In power-by-wire systems, electrical actuators are used in favour of hydraulic pistons.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] The power is carried to the actuators by electrical cables.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] These are lighter than hydraulic pipes, easier to install and maintain, and more reliable.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] Elements of the F-35 flight control system are power-by-wire.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] The actuators in such an electro-hydrostatic actuation (EHA) system are self-contained hydraulic devices, small closed-circuit hydraulic systems.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] The overall aim is towards more- or all-electric aircraft and an early example of the approach was the Avro Vulcan.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] Serious consideration was given to using the approach on the Airbus A380.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] A fly-by-wire (FBW) system replaces manual flight control of an aircraft with an electronic interface.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] The movements of flight controls are converted to electronic signals transmitted by wires (hence the term *fly-by-wire*), and flight control computers determine how to move the actuators at each control surface to provide the expected response.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] Commands from the computers are also input without the pilot's knowledge to stabilize the aircraft and perform other tasks.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] Electronics for aircraft flight control systems are part of the field known as avionics.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] Fly-by-optics, also known as *fly-by-light*, is a further development using fiber-optic cables.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] These may be used in many unmanned aerial vehicles (UAVs) and 6th generation fighter aircraft.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] Two promising approaches are flexible wings, and fluidics.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] In flexible wings, also known as "morphing aerofoils", much or all of a wing surface can change shape in flight to deflect air flow much like an ornithopter.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] Adaptive compliant wings are a military and commercial effort.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] The X-53 Active Aeroelastic Wing was a US Air Force, NASA, and Boeing effort.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] Notable efforts have also been made by FlexSys, who have conducted flight tests using flexible aerofoils retrofitted to a Gulf stream III aircraft.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] In this use, active flow control promises simplicity and lower mass, costs (up to half less), and inertia and response times.
[src:avionics-systems/aircraft-flight-control-system] This was demonstrated in the Demon UAV, which flew for the first time in the UK in September 2010.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] The term "avionics" was coined in 1949 by Philip J.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] Klass, senior editor at *Aviation Week & Space Technology* magazine as a portmanteau of "**aviation electronics**".
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] Radio communication was first used in aircraft just prior to World War I.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] The first airborne radios were in zeppelins, but the military sparked development of light radio sets that could be carried by heavier-than-air craft, so that aerial reconnaissance biplanes could report their observations immediately in case they were shot down.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] The first experimental radio transmission from an airplane was conducted by the U.S.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] The first aircraft radios transmitted by radiotelegraphy.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] They required a two-seat aircraft with a second crewman who operated a telegraph key to spell out messages in Morse code.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] During World War I, amplitude modulation voice two way radio sets were made possible in 1917 (see TM (triode)) by the development of the triode vacuum tube, which were simple enough that the pilot in a single seat aircraft could use it while flying.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] Radar, the central technology used today in aircraft navigation and air traffic control, was developed by several nations, mainly in secret, as an air defense system in the 1930s during the runup to World War II.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] Many modern avionics have their origins in World War II wartime developments.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] For example, autopilot systems that are commonplace today began as specialized systems to help bomber planes fly steadily enough to hit precision targets from high altitudes.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] Britain's 1940 decision to share its radar technology with its U.S. ally, particularly the magnetron vacuum tube, in the famous Tizard Mission, significantly shortened the war.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] Modern avionics is a substantial portion of military aircraft spending.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] Aircraft like the F-15E and the now retired F-14 have roughly 20 percent of their budget spent on avionics.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] Most modern helicopters now have budget splits of 60/40 in favour of avionics.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] The civilian market has also seen a growth in cost of avionics.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] Flight control systems (fly-by-wire) and new navigation needs brought on by tighter airspaces, have pushed up development costs.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] The major change has been the recent boom in consumer flying.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] As more people begin to use planes as their primary method of transportation, more elaborate methods of controlling aircraft safely in these high restrictive airspaces have been invented.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] Avionics plays a heavy role in modernization initiatives like the Federal Aviation Administration's (FAA) Next Generation Air Transportation System project in the United States and the Single European Sky ATM Research (SESAR) initiative in Europe.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] The cockpit or, in larger aircraft, under the cockpit of an aircraft or in a movable nosecone, is a typical location for avionic bay equipment, including control, monitoring, communication, navigation, weather, and anti-collision systems.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] The majority of aircraft power their avionics using 14- or 28‑volt DC electrical systems; however, larger, more sophisticated aircraft (such as airliners or military combat aircraft) have AC systems operating at 115 volts 400 Hz, AC.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] International standards for avionics equipment are prepared by the Airlines Electronic Engineering Committee and published by ARINC.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] Communications connect the flight deck to the ground and the flight deck to the passengers.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] On‑board communications are provided by public-address systems and aircraft intercoms.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] The VHF aviation communication system works on the airband of 118.000 MHz to 136.975 MHz.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] Each channel is spaced from the adjacent ones by 8.33 kHz in Europe, 25 kHz elsewhere.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] VHF is also used for line of sight communication such as aircraft-to-aircraft and aircraft-to-ATC.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] Amplitude modulation is used, and the conversation is performed in simplex mode.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] Aircraft communication can also take place using HF (especially for trans-oceanic flights) or satellite communication.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] Air navigation is the determination of position and direction on or above the surface of the Earth.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] Avionics can use satellite navigation systems (such as GPS, WAAS, EGNOS and GBAS/LAAS), inertial navigation system (INS), ground-based radio navigation systems (such as VOR or LORAN), or any combination thereof.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] Some navigation systems such as GPS calculate the position automatically and display it to the flight crew on moving map displays.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] Older ground-based Navigation systems such as VOR or LORAN requires a pilot or navigator to plot the intersection of signals on a paper map to determine an aircraft's location; modern systems calculate the position automatically and display it to the flight crew on moving map displays.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] The first hints of glass cockpits emerged in the 1970s when flight-worthy cathode ray tube (CRT) screens began to replace electromechanical displays, gauges and instruments.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] A "glass" cockpit refers to the use of computer monitors instead of gauges and other analog displays.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] Aircraft were getting progressively more displays, dials and information dashboards that eventually competed for space and pilot attention.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] In the 1970s, the average aircraft had more than 100 cockpit instruments and controls.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] Glass cockpits started to come into being with the Gulfstream G‑IV private jet in 1985.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] One of the key challenges in glass cockpits is to balance how much control is automated and how much the pilot should do manually.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] Generally they try to automate flight operations while keeping the pilot constantly informed.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] Aircraft have means of automatically controlling flight.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] Autopilot was first invented by Lawrence Sperry during World War I to fly bomber planes steady enough to hit accurate targets from 25,000 feet.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] When it was first adopted by the U.S. military, a Honeywell engineer sat in the back seat with bolt cutters to disconnect the autopilot in case of emergency.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] Nowadays most commercial planes are equipped with aircraft flight control systems in order to reduce pilot error and workload at landing or takeoff.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] The first simple commercial auto-pilots were used to control heading and altitude and had limited authority on things like thrust and flight control surfaces.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] In helicopters, auto-stabilization was used in a similar way.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] The first systems were electromechanical.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] The advent of fly-by-wire and electro-actuated flight surfaces (rather than the traditional hydraulic) has increased safety.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] As with displays and instruments, critical devices that were electro-mechanical had a finite life.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] With safety critical systems, the software is very strictly tested.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] Fuel Quantity Indication System (FQIS) monitors the amount of fuel aboard.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] Using various sensors, such as capacitance tubes, temperature sensors, densitometers & level sensors, the FQIS computer calculates the mass of fuel remaining on board.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] Fuel Control and Monitoring System (FCMS) reports fuel remaining on board in a similar manner, but, by controlling pumps & valves, also manages fuel transfers around various tanks.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] To supplement air traffic control, most large transport aircraft and many smaller ones use a traffic alert and collision avoidance system (TCAS), which can detect the location of nearby aircraft, and provide instructions for avoiding a midair collision.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] Smaller aircraft may use simpler traffic alerting systems such as TPAS, which are passive (they do not actively interrogate the transponders of other aircraft) and do not provide advisories for conflict resolution.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] To help avoid controlled flight into terrain (CFIT), aircraft use systems such as ground-proximity warning systems (GPWS), which use radar altimeters as a key element.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] One of the major weaknesses of GPWS is the lack of "look-ahead" information, because it only provides altitude above terrain "look-down".
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] In order to overcome this weakness, modern aircraft use a terrain awareness warning system (TAWS).
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] Commercial aircraft cockpit data recorders, commonly known as "black boxes", store flight information and audio from the cockpit.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] They are often recovered from an aircraft after a crash to determine control settings and other parameters during the incident.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] Weather systems such as weather radar (typically Arinc 708 on commercial aircraft) and lightning detectors are important for aircraft flying at night or in instrument meteorological conditions, where it is not possible for pilots to see the weather ahead.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] Heavy precipitation (as sensed by radar) or severe turbulence (as sensed by lightning activity) are both indications of strong convective activity and severe turbulence, and weather systems allow pilots to deviate around these areas.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] Lightning detectors like the Stormscope or Strikefinder have become inexpensive enough that they are practical for light aircraft.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] In addition to radar and lightning detection, observations and extended radar pictures (such as NEXRAD) are now available through satellite data connections, allowing pilots to see weather conditions far beyond the range of their own in-flight systems.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] Modern displays allow weather information to be integrated with moving maps, terrain, and traffic onto a single screen, greatly simplifying navigation.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] Modern weather systems also include wind shear and turbulence detection and terrain and traffic warning systems.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] In‑plane weather avionics are especially popular in Africa, India, and other countries where air-travel is a growing market, but ground support is not as well developed.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] There has been a progression towards centralized control of the multiple complex systems fitted to aircraft, including engine monitoring and management.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] Health and usage monitoring systems (HUMS) are integrated with aircraft management computers to give maintainers early warnings of parts that will need replacement.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] The integrated modular avionics concept proposes an integrated architecture with application software portable across an assembly of common hardware modules.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] It has been used in fourth generation jet fighters and the latest generation of airliners.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] Military aircraft have been designed either to deliver a weapon or to be the eyes and ears of other weapon systems.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] The vast array of sensors available to the military is used for whatever tactical means required.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] As with aircraft management, the bigger sensor platforms (like the E‑3D, JSTARS, ASTOR, Nimrod MRA4, Merlin HM Mk 1) have mission-management computers.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] Police and EMS aircraft also carry sophisticated tactical sensors.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] While aircraft communications provide the backbone for safe flight, the tactical systems are designed to withstand the rigors of the battlefield.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] UHF, VHF Tactical (30–88 MHz) and SatCom systems combined with ECCM methods, and cryptography secure the communications.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] Data links such as Link 11, 16, 22 and BOWMAN, JTRS and even TETRA provide the means of transmitting data (such as images, targeting information etc.).
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] Airborne radar was one of the first tactical sensors.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] The benefit of altitude providing range has meant a significant focus on airborne radar technologies.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] Radars include airborne early warning, anti-submarine warfare, and even weather radar (Arinc 708) and ground tracking/proximity radar.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] The military uses radar in fast jets to help pilots fly at low levels.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] While the civil market has had weather radar for a while, there are strict rules about using it to navigate the aircraft.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] Dipping sonar fitted to a range of military helicopters allows the helicopter to protect shipping assets from submarines or surface threats.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] Maritime support aircraft can drop active and passive sonar devices (sonobuoys) and these are also used to determine the location of enemy submarines.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] Electro-optic systems include devices such as the head-up display (HUD), forward looking infrared (FLIR), infrared search and track and other passive infrared devices (Passive infrared sensor).
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] These are all used to provide imagery and information to the flight crew.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] This imagery is used for everything from search and rescue to navigational aids and target acquisition.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] Electronic support measures and defensive aids systems are used extensively to gather information about threats or possible threats.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] They can be used to launch devices (in some cases automatically) to counter direct threats against the aircraft.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] They are also used to determine the state of a threat and identify it.
[src:avionics-systems/avionics] The avionics systems in military, commercial and advanced models of civilian aircraft are interconnected using an avionics databus.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] A **cockpit**, also called **flight deck**, is the area, on the front part of an aircraft, spacecraft, or submersible, from which a pilot controls the vehicle.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] The cockpit of an aircraft contains flight instruments on an instrument panel, and the controls that enable the pilot to fly the aircraft.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] In most airliners, a door separates the cockpit/Flight Deck from the aircraft cabin.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] After the September 11, 2001 attacks, all major airlines fortified their cockpits against access by hijackers.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] The word cockpit seems to have been used as a nautical term in the 17th century, without reference to cock fighting.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] It referred to an area in the rear of a ship where the cockswain's station was located, the cockswain being the pilot of a smaller "boat" that could be dispatched from the ship to board another ship or to bring people ashore.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] The word "cockswain" in turn derives from the old English terms for "boat-servant" (*coque* is the French word for "shell"; and *swain* was old English for boy or servant).
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] The midshipmen and master's mates were later berthed in the cockpit, and it served as the action station for the ship's surgeon and his mates during battle.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] Thus by the 18th century, "cockpit" had come to designate an area in the rear lower deck of a warship where the wounded were taken.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] The same term later came to designate the place from which a sailing vessel is steered, because it is also located in the rear, and is often in a well or "pit".
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] However, a convergent etymology does involve reference to cock fighting.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] Thus the word Cockpit came to mean a control center.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] The original meaning of "cockpit", first attested in the 1580s, is "a pit for fighting cocks", referring to the place where cockfights were held.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] This meaning no doubt influenced both lines of evolution of the term, since a cockpit in this sense was a tight enclosure where a great deal of stress or tension would occur.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] From about 1935, *cockpit* came to be used informally to refer to the driver's cabin, especially in high performance cars, and this is official terminology used to describe the compartment that the driver occupies in a Formula One car.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] In an airliner, the cockpit is usually referred to as the *flight deck*, the term deriving from its use by the RAF for the separate, upper platform in large flying boats where the pilot and co-pilot sat.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] Currently, in the USA and many other countries, the term cockpit is used interchangeably for airliners.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] However, in the Aerospace Industry, a general rule of thumb is that if it is a civil air transport airliner in which you can walk into the controls area of the aircraft (or spacecraft), it is referred to as a "Flight Deck".
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] If you have to climb or crawl into it, it is referred to as the "cockpit".
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] The seat of a powerboat racing craft is also referred to as the cockpit.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] The first airplane with an enclosed cabin appeared in 1912 on the Avro Type F; however, during the early 1920s there were many passenger aircraft in which the crew remained open to the air while the passengers sat in a cabin.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] Military biplanes and the first single-engined fighters and attack aircraft also had open cockpits, some as late as the Second World War when enclosed cockpits became the norm.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] The largest impediment to having closed cabins was the material used to make the windows.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] Prior to Perspex becoming available in 1933, windows were either safety glass, which was heavy, or cellulose nitrate (i.e.: guncotton), which yellowed quickly and was extremely flammable.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] In the mid-1920s many aircraft manufacturers began using enclosed cockpits for the first time.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] Early airplanes with closed cockpits include the 1924 Fokker F.VII, the 1926 German Junkers W 34 transport, the 1926 Ford Trimotor, the 1927 Lockheed Vega, the *Spirit of St.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] Louis* and the passenger aircraft manufactured by the Douglas and Boeing companies during the mid-1930s.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] Open-cockpit airplanes were almost extinct by the mid-1950s, with the exception of training planes, crop-dusters and homebuilt aircraft designs.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] Cockpit windows may be equipped with a sun shield.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] Most cockpits have windows that can be opened when the aircraft is on the ground.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] Nearly all glass windows in large aircraft have an anti-reflective coating, and an internal heating element to melt ice.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] Smaller aircraft may be equipped with a transparent aircraft canopy.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] In most cockpits the pilot's control column or joystick is located centrally (centre stick), although in some military fast jets the side-stick is located on the right hand side.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] In some commercial airliners (i.e.: Airbus—which features the glass cockpit concept) both pilots use a side-stick located on the outboard side, so Captain's side-stick on the left and First-officer's seat on the right.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] Except for some helicopters, the *right seat* in the cockpit of an aircraft is the seat used by the co-pilot.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] The captain or pilot in command sits in the *left seat*, so that they can operate the throttles and other pedestal instruments with their right hand.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] The tradition has been maintained to this day, with the co-pilot on the right hand side.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] The layout of the cockpit, especially in the military fast jet, has undergone standardisation, both within and between aircraft, manufacturers and even nations.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] An important development was the "Basic Six" pattern, later the "Basic T", developed from 1937 onwards by the Royal Air Force, designed to optimise pilot instrument scanning.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] Ergonomics and Human Factors concerns are important in the design of modern cockpits.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] The layout and function of cockpit displays controls are designed to increase pilot situation awareness without causing information overload.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] In the past, many cockpits, especially in fighter aircraft, limited the size of the pilots that could fit into them.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] Now, cockpits are being designed to accommodate from the 1st percentile female physical size to the 99th percentile male size.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] In the design of the cockpit in a military fast jet, the traditional "knobs and dials" associated with the cockpit are mainly absent.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] Instrument panels are now almost wholly replaced by electronic displays, which are themselves often re-configurable to save space.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] While some hard-wired dedicated switches must still be used for reasons of integrity and safety, many traditional controls are replaced by multi-function re-configurable controls or so-called "soft keys".
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] Controls are incorporated onto the stick and throttle to enable the pilot to maintain a head-up and eyes-out position – the Hands On Throttle And Stick or HOTAS concept.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] These controls may be then further augmented by control media such as head pointing with a Helmet Mounted Sighting System or Direct voice input (DVI).
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] Advances in auditory displays allow for Direct Voice Output of aircraft status information and for the spatial localisation of warning sounds for improved monitoring of aircraft systems.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] The layout of control panels in modern airliners has become largely unified across the industry.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] The majority of the systems-related controls (such as electrical, fuel, hydraulics and pressurization) for example, are usually located in the ceiling on an overhead panel.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] Radios are generally placed on a panel between the pilot's seats known as the pedestal.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] Automatic flight controls such as the autopilot are usually placed just below the windscreen and above the main instrument panel on the glareshield.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] A central concept in the design of the cockpit is the Design Eye Position or "DEP", from which point all displays should be visible.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] Most modern cockpits will also include some kind of integrated warning system.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] A study undertaken in 2013, to assess methods for cockpit-user menu navigation, found that touchscreen produced the "best scores".
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] In the modern electronic cockpit, the electronic flight instruments usually regarded as essential are MFD, PFD, ND, EICAS, FMS/CDU and back-up instruments.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] A Mode control panel, usually a long narrow panel located centrally in front of the pilot, may be used to control heading, speed, altitude, vertical speed, vertical navigation and lateral navigation.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] It may also be used to engage or disengage both the autopilot and the autothrottle.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] The panel as an area is usually referred to as the "glareshield panel".
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] MCP is a Boeing designation (that has been informally adopted as a generic name for the unit/panel) for a unit that allows for the selection and parameter setting of the different autoflight functions, the same unit on an Airbus aircraft is referred to as the FCU (Flight Control unit).
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] The primary flight display is usually located in a prominent position, either centrally or on either side of the cockpit.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] It will in most cases include a digitized presentation of the attitude indicator, air speed and altitude indicators (usually as a tape display) and the vertical speed indicator.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] It will in many cases include some form of heading indicator and ILS/VOR deviation indicators.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] In many cases an indicator of the engaged and armed autoflight system modes will be present along with some form of indication of the selected values for altitude, speed, vertical speed and heading.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] It may be pilot selectable to swap with the ND.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] A navigation display, which may be adjacent to the PFD, shows the route and information on the next waypoint, wind speed and wind direction.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] It may be pilot selectable to swap with the PFD.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] The pilot may select display of information by means of button press.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] The flight management system/control and/or display unit may be used by the pilot to enter and check for the following information: flight plan, speed control, navigation control, etc.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] In a less prominent part of the cockpit, in case of failure of the other instruments, there will be a battery-powered integrated standby instrument system along with a magnetic compass, showing essential flight information such as speed, altitude, attitude and heading.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] In the U.S. the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) and the National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA) have researched the ergonomic aspects of cockpit design and have conducted investigations of airline industry accidents.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] Cockpit design disciplines include Cognitive science, Neuroscience, Human–computer interaction, Human Factors Engineering, Anthropometry and Ergonomics.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] Aircraft designs have adopted the fully digital "glass cockpit".
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] In such designs, instruments and gauges, including navigational map displays, use a user interface markup language known as ARINC 661.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] This standard defines the interface between an independent cockpit display system, generally produced by a single manufacturer, and the avionics equipment and user applications it is required to support, by means of displays and controls, often made by different manufacturers.
[src:avionics-systems/cockpit] The separation between the overall display system, and the applications driving it, allows for specialization and independence.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] The pilot may not be fully aware of all the control outputs acting to affect the outcome, only that the aircraft is reacting as expected.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] The fly-by-wire computers act to stabilize the aircraft and adjust the flying characteristics without the pilot's involvement, and to prevent the pilot from operating outside of the aircraft's safe performance envelope.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] Mechanical and hydro-mechanical flight control systems are relatively heavy and require careful routing of flight control cables through the aircraft by systems of pulleys, cranks, tension cables and hydraulic pipes.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] Both systems often require redundant backup to deal with failures, which increases weight.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] Both have limited ability to compensate for changing aerodynamic conditions.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] Dangerous characteristics such as stalling, spinning and pilot-induced oscillation (PIO), which depend mainly on the stability and structure of the aircraft rather than the control system itself, are dependent on the pilot's actions.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] The term "fly-by-wire" implies a purely electrically signaled control system.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] It is used in the general sense of computer-configured controls, where a computer system is interposed between the operator and the final control actuators or surfaces.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] This modifies the manual inputs of the pilot in accordance with control parameters.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] Side-sticks or conventional flight control yokes can be used to fly fly-by-wire aircraft.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] A fly-by-wire aircraft can be lighter than a similar design with conventional controls.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] These include the vertical and horizontal stabilizers (fin and tailplane) that are (normally) at the rear of the fuselage.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] If these structures can be reduced in size, airframe weight is reduced.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] The advantages of fly-by-wire controls were first exploited by the military and then in the commercial airline market.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] The Airbus series of airliners used full-authority fly-by-wire controls beginning with their A320 series, see A320 flight control (though some limited fly-by-wire functions existed on A310 aircraft).
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] Boeing followed with their 777 and later designs.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] A pilot commands the flight control computer to make the aircraft perform a certain action, such as pitch the aircraft up, or roll to one side, by moving the control column or sidestick.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] The flight control computer then calculates what control surface movements will cause the plane to perform that action and issues those commands to the electronic controllers for each surface.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] The controllers at each surface receive these commands and then move actuators attached to the control surface until it has moved to where the flight control computer commanded it to.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] The controllers measure the position of the flight control surface with sensors such as LVDTs.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] Fly-by-wire control systems allow aircraft computers to perform tasks without pilot input.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] Automatic stability systems operate in this way.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] Gyroscopes and sensors such as accelerometers are mounted in an aircraft to sense rotation on the pitch, roll and yaw axes.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] Any movement (from straight and level flight for example) results in signals to the computer, which can automatically move control actuators to stabilize the aircraft.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] While traditional mechanical or hydraulic control systems usually fail gradually, the loss of all flight control computers immediately renders the aircraft uncontrollable.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] For this reason, most fly-by-wire systems incorporate either redundant computers (triplex, quadruplex etc.), some kind of mechanical or hydraulic backup or a combination of both.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] A "mixed" control system with mechanical backup feeds any rudder elevation directly back to the pilot and therefore makes closed loop (feedback) systems senseless.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] Aircraft systems may be quadruplexed (four independent channels) to prevent loss of signals in the case of failure of one or even two channels.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] High performance aircraft that have fly-by-wire controls (also called CCVs or Control-Configured Vehicles) may be deliberately designed to have low or even negative stability in some flight regimes – rapid-reacting CCV controls can electronically stabilize the lack of natural stability.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] Pre-flight safety checks of a fly-by-wire system are often performed using built-in test equipment (BITE).
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] A number of control movement steps can be automatically performed, reducing workload of the pilot or groundcrew and speeding up flight-checks.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] Some aircraft, the Panavia Tornado for example, retain a very basic hydro-mechanical backup system for limited flight control capability on losing electrical power; in the case of the Tornado this allows rudimentary control of the stabilators only for pitch and roll axis movements.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] Servo-electrically operated control surfaces were first tested in the 1930s on the Soviet Tupolev ANT-20.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] Long runs of mechanical and hydraulic connections were replaced with wires and electric servos.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] In 1934, Karl Otto Altvater filed a patent about the automatic-electronic system, which flared the aircraft, when it was close to the ground.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] In 1941, while being an engineer at Siemens, developed and tested the first fly-by-wire system for the Heinkel He 111, in which the aircraft was fully controlled by electronic impulses.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] The first non-experimental aircraft that was designed and flown (in 1958) with a fly-by-wire flight control system was the Avro Canada CF-105 Arrow, the North American A-5 Vigilante which flew later the same year would be the first aircraft to reach operational service with a fly by wire system.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] This system also included solid-state components and system redundancy, was designed to be integrated with a computerised navigation and automatic search and track radar, was flyable from ground control with data uplink and downlink, and provided artificial feel (feedback) to the pilot.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] The first electronic fly-by-wire testbed operated by the U.S.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] Air Force was a Boeing B-47E Stratojet (Ser.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] The first pure electronic fly-by-wire aircraft with no mechanical or hydraulic backup was the Apollo Lunar Landing Training Vehicle (LLTV), first flown in 1968.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] This was preceded in 1964 by the Lunar Landing Research Vehicle (LLRV) which pioneered fly-by-wire flight with no mechanical backup.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] Control was through a digital computer with three analog redundant channels.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] At about the same time in the United Kingdom a trainer variant of the British Hawker Hunter fighter was modified at the British Royal Aircraft Establishment with fly-by-wire flight controls for the right-seat pilot.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] In the UK the two seater Avro 707C was flown with a Fairey system with mechanical backup in the early to mid-60s.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] The program was curtailed when the air-frame ran out of flight time.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] In 1972, the first digital fly-by-wire fixed-wing aircraft without a mechanical backup to take to the air was an F-8 Crusader, which had been modified electronically by NASA of the United States as a test aircraft; the F-8 used the Apollo guidance, navigation and control hardware.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] The Airbus A320 began service in 1988 as the first mass-produced airliner with digital fly-by-wire controls.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] As of June 2024, over 11,000 A320 family aircraft, variants included, are operational around the world, making it one of the best-selling commercial jets.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] Boeing chose fly-by-wire flight controls for the 777 in 1994, departing from traditional cable and pulley systems.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] In addition to overseeing the aircraft's flight control, the FBW offered "envelope protection", which guaranteed that the system would step in to avoid accidental mishandling, stalls, or excessive structural stress on the aircraft.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] The 777 used ARINC 629 buses to connect primary flight computers (PFCs) with actuator-control electronics units (ACEs).
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] Every PFC housed three 32-bit microprocessors, including a Motorola 68040, an Intel 80486, and an AMD 29050, all programmed in Ada programming language.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] All fly-by-wire flight control systems eliminate the complexity, fragility and weight of the mechanical circuit of the hydromechanical or electromechanical flight control systems – each being replaced with electronic circuits.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] The control mechanisms in the cockpit now operate signal transducers, which in turn generate the appropriate commands.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] These are next processed by an electronic controller—either an analog one, or (more modernly) a digital one.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] Aircraft and spacecraft autopilots are now part of the electronic controller.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] The hydraulic circuits are similar except that mechanical servo valves are replaced with electrically controlled servo valves, operated by the electronic controller.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] This is the simplest and earliest configuration of an analog fly-by-wire flight control system.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] In this configuration, the flight control systems must simulate "feel".
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] The electronic controller controls electrical devices that provide the appropriate "feel" forces on the manual controls.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] This was used in Concorde, the first production fly-by-wire airliner.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] A digital fly-by-wire flight control system can be extended from its analog counterpart.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] Digital signal processing can receive and interpret input from multiple sensors simultaneously (such as the altimeters and the pitot tubes) and adjust the controls in real time.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] The computers sense position and force inputs from pilot controls and aircraft sensors.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] They then solve differential equations related to the aircraft's equations of motion to determine the appropriate command signals for the flight controls to execute the intentions of the pilot.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] The programming of the digital computers enable flight envelope protection.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] These protections are tailored to an aircraft's handling characteristics to stay within aerodynamic and structural limitations of the aircraft.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] Software can also be included that stabilize the flight-control inputs to avoid pilot-induced oscillations.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] Since the flight-control computers continuously feedback the environment, pilot's workloads can be reduced.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] This also enables military aircraft with relaxed stability.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] The primary benefit for such aircraft is more maneuverability during combat and training flights, and the so-called "carefree handling" because stalling, spinning and other undesirable performances are prevented automatically by the computers.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] Digital flight control systems (DFCS) enable inherently unstable combat aircraft, such as the Lockheed F-117 Nighthawk and the Northrop Grumman B-2 Spirit flying wing to fly in usable and safe manners.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] The United States Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) has adopted the RTCA/DO-178C, titled "Software Considerations in Airborne Systems and Equipment Certification", as the certification standard for aviation software.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] Any safety-critical component in a digital fly-by-wire system including applications of the laws of aeronautics and computer operating systems will need to be certified to DO-178C Level A or B, depending on the class of aircraft, which is applicable for preventing potential catastrophic failures.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] Nevertheless, the top concern for computerized, digital, fly-by-wire systems is reliability, even more so than for analog electronic control systems.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] This is because the digital computers that are running software are often the only control path between the pilot and aircraft's flight control surfaces.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] If the computer software crashes for any reason, the pilot may be unable to control an aircraft.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] Hence virtually all fly-by-wire flight control systems are either triply or quadruply redundant in their computers and electronics.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] These have three or four flight-control computers operating in parallel and three or four separate data buses connecting them with each control surface.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] The multiple redundant flight control computers continuously monitor each other's output.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] If one computer begins to give aberrant results for any reason, potentially including software or hardware failures or flawed input data, then the combined system is designed to exclude the results from that computer in deciding the appropriate actions for the flight controls.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] Depending on specific system details there may be the potential to reboot an aberrant flight control computer, or to reincorporate its inputs if they return to agreement.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] Complex logic exists to deal with multiple failures, which may prompt the system to revert to simpler back-up modes.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] In addition, most of the early digital fly-by-wire aircraft also had an analog electrical, mechanical, or hydraulic back-up flight control system.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] This backup system served to reduce the risk of total flight control system failure ever happening because of a general-purpose flight software fault that had escaped notice in the other four computers.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] For airliners, flight-control redundancy improves their safety, but fly-by-wire control systems, which are physically lighter and have lower maintenance demands than conventional controls also improve economy, both in terms of cost of ownership and for in-flight economy.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] In certain designs with limited relaxed stability in the pitch axis, for example the Boeing 777, the flight control system may allow the aircraft to fly at a more aerodynamically efficient angle of attack than a conventionally stable design.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] Modern airliners also commonly feature computerized Full-Authority Digital Engine Control systems (FADECs) that control their engines, air inlets, fuel storage and distribution system, in a similar fashion to the way that FBW controls the flight control surfaces.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] This allows the engine output to be continually varied for the most efficient usage possible.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] The second generation Embraer E-Jet family gained a 1.5% efficiency improvement over the first generation from the fly-by-wire system, which enabled a reduction from 280 ft.² to 250 ft.² for the horizontal stabilizer on the E190/195 variants.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] Airbus and Boeing differ in their approaches to implementing fly-by-wire systems in commercial aircraft.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] Since the Airbus A320, Airbus flight-envelope control systems always retain ultimate flight control when flying under normal law and will not permit pilots to violate aircraft performance limits unless they choose to fly under alternate law.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] This strategy has been continued on subsequent Airbus airliners.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] Boeing airliners, such as the Boeing 777, allow the pilots to completely override the computerized flight control system, permitting the aircraft to be flown outside of its usual flight control envelope.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] The advent of FADEC (Full Authority Digital Engine Control) engines permits operation of the flight control systems and autothrottles for the engines to be fully integrated.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] On modern military aircraft other systems such as autostabilization, navigation, radar and weapons system are all integrated with the flight control systems.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] FADEC allows maximum performance to be extracted from the aircraft without fear of engine misoperation, aircraft damage or high pilot workloads.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] In the civil field, the integration increases flight safety and economy.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] Airbus fly-by-wire aircraft are protected from dangerous situations such as low-speed stall or overstressing by flight envelope protection.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] As a result, in such conditions, the flight control systems commands the engines to increase thrust without pilot intervention.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] In economy cruise modes, the flight control systems adjust the throttles and fuel tank selections precisely.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] FADEC reduces rudder drag needed to compensate for sideways flight from unbalanced engine thrust.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] On the A330/A340 family, fuel is transferred between the main (wing and center fuselage) tanks and a fuel tank in the horizontal stabilizer, to optimize the aircraft's center of gravity during cruise flight.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] The fuel management controls keep the aircraft's center of gravity accurately trimmed with fuel weight, rather than drag-inducing aerodynamic trims in the elevators.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] Fly-by-optics is sometimes used instead of fly-by-wire because it offers a higher data transfer rate, immunity to electromagnetic interference and lighter weight.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] In most cases, the cables are just changed from electrical to optical fiber cables.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] Sometimes it is referred to as "fly-by-light" due to its use of fiber optics.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] The data generated by the software and interpreted by the controller remain the same.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] Fly-by-light has the effect of decreasing electro-magnetic disturbances to sensors in comparison to more common fly-by-wire control systems.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] The Kawasaki P-1 is the first production aircraft in the world to be equipped with such a flight control system.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] Having eliminated the mechanical transmission circuits in fly-by-wire flight control systems, the next step is to replace the bulky and heavy hydraulic circuits with electrical power circuit.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] The power circuits power electrical or self-contained electrohydraulic actuators that are controlled by the digital flight control computers.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] All benefits of digital fly-by-wire are retained since the power-by-wire components are strictly complementary to the fly-by-wire components.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] The biggest benefits are weight savings, the possibility of redundant power circuits and tighter integration between the aircraft flight control systems and its avionics systems.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] The absence of hydraulics greatly reduces maintenance costs.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] This system is used in the Lockheed Martin F-35 Lightning II and in Airbus A380 backup flight controls.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] The Boeing 787 and Airbus A350 also incorporate electrically powered backup flight controls which remain operational even in the event of a total loss of hydraulic power.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] Wiring adds a considerable amount of weight to an aircraft; therefore, researchers are exploring implementing fly-by-wireless solutions.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] Fly-by-wireless systems are very similar to fly-by-wire systems, however, instead of using a wired protocol for the physical layer a wireless protocol is employed.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] In addition to reducing weight, implementing a wireless solution has the potential to reduce costs throughout an aircraft's life cycle.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] For example, many key failure points associated with wire and connectors will be eliminated thus hours spent troubleshooting wires and connectors will be reduced.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] Furthermore, engineering costs could potentially decrease because less time would be spent on designing wiring installations, late changes in an aircraft's design would be easier to manage, etc.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] A newer flight control system, called intelligent flight control system (IFCS), is an extension of modern digital fly-by-wire flight control systems.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] The aim is to intelligently compensate for aircraft damage and failure during flight, such as automatically using engine thrust and other avionics to compensate for severe failures such as loss of hydraulics, loss of rudder, loss of ailerons, loss of an engine, etc.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] Several demonstrations were made on a flight simulator where a Cessna-trained small-aircraft pilot successfully landed a heavily damaged full-size concept jet, without prior experience with large-body jet aircraft.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] This development is being spearheaded by NASA Dryden Flight Research Center.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] It is reported that enhancements are mostly software upgrades to existing fully computerized digital fly-by-wire flight control systems.
[src:avionics-systems/fly-by-wire] The Dassault Falcon 7X and Embraer Legacy 500 business jets have flight computers that can partially compensate for engine-out scenarios by adjusting thrust levels and control inputs, but still require pilots to respond appropriately.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] A **head-up display**, also known as a **HUD** (/hʌd/) or **head-up guidance system** (**HGS**), is any transparent display that presents data without requiring users to look away from their usual viewpoints.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] The origin of the name stems from a pilot being able to view information with the head positioned "up" and looking forward, instead of angled down looking at lower instruments.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] A HUD also has the advantage that the pilot's eyes do not need to refocus to view the outside after looking at the optically nearer instruments.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] Although they were initially developed for military aviation, HUDs are now used in commercial aircraft, automobiles, and other (mostly professional) applications.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] Head-up displays were a precursor technology to augmented reality (AR), incorporating a subset of the features needed for the full AR experience, but lacking the necessary registration and tracking between the virtual content and the user's real-world environment.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] A typical HUD contains three primary components: a *projector unit*, a *combiner*, and a *video generation computer*.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] The projection unit in a typical HUD is an optical collimator setup: a convex lens or concave mirror with a cathode-ray tube, light emitting diode display, or liquid crystal display at its focus.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] This setup (a design that has been around since the invention of the reflector sight in 1900) produces an image where the light is collimated, i.e., the focal point is perceived to be at infinity.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] The combiner is typically an angled flat piece of glass (a beam splitter) located directly in front of the viewer, that redirects the projected image from projector in such a way as to see the field of view and the projected infinity image at the same time.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] Combiners may have special coatings that reflect the monochromatic light projected onto it from the projector unit while allowing all other wavelengths of light to pass through.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] In some optical layouts combiners may also have a curved surface to refocus the image from the projector.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] The computer provides the interface between the HUD (i.e., the projection unit) and the systems/data to be displayed and generates the imagery and symbology to be displayed by the projection unit.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] Other than fixed mounted HUD, there are also head-mounted displays (HMDs).
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] These include helmet-mounted displays (both abbreviated HMDs), forms of HUD that feature a display element that moves with the orientation of the user's head.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] Many modern fighters (such as the F/A-18, F-16, and Eurofighter) use both a HUD and HMD concurrently.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] The F-35 Lightning II was designed without a HUD, relying solely on the HMD, making it the first modern military fighter not to have a fixed HUD.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] Newer micro-display imaging technologies are being introduced, including liquid-crystal display (LCD), liquid crystal on silicon (LCoS), digital micro-mirrors (DMD), and organic light-emitting diode (OLED).
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] HUDs evolved from the reflector sight, a pre-World War II parallax-free optical sight technology for military fighter aircraft.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] The gyro gunsight added a reticle that moved based on the speed and turn rate to solve for the amount of lead needed to hit a target while maneuvering.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] During the early 1940s, the Telecommunications Research Establishment (TRE), in charge of UK radar development, found that Royal Air Force (RAF) night fighter pilots were having a hard time reacting to the verbal instruction of the radar operator as they approached their targets.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] They experimented with the addition of a second radar display for the pilot, but found they had trouble looking up from the lit screen into the dark sky in order to find the target.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] In October 1942 they had successfully combined the image from the radar tube with a projection from their standard GGS Mk.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] II gyro gunsight on a flat area of the windscreen, and later in the gunsight itself.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] A key upgrade was the move from the original AI Mk.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] IV radar to the microwave-frequency AI Mk.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] VIII radar found on the de Havilland Mosquito night fighter.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] This set produced an artificial horizon that further eased head-up flying.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] In 1955 the US Navy's Office of Naval Research and Development did some research with a mockup HUD concept unit along with a sidestick controller in an attempt to ease the pilot's burden flying modern jet aircraft and make the instrumentation less complicated during flight.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] While their research was never incorporated in any aircraft of that time, the crude HUD mockup they built had all the features of today's modern HUD units.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] HUD technology was next advanced by the Royal Navy in the Buccaneer, the prototype of which first flew on 30 April 1958.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] The aircraft was designed to fly at very low altitudes at very high speeds and drop bombs in engagements lasting seconds.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] As such, there was no time for the pilot to look up from the instruments to a bombsight.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] This led to the concept of a "Strike Sight" that would combine altitude, airspeed and the gun/bombsight into a single gunsight-like display.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] There was fierce competition between supporters of the new HUD design and supporters of the old electro-mechanical gunsight, with the HUD being described as a radical, even foolhardy option.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] The Air Arm branch of the UK Ministry of Defence sponsored the development of a Strike Sight.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] The Royal Aircraft Establishment (RAE) designed the equipment and the earliest usage of the term "head-up-display" can be traced to this time.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] Production units were built by Rank Cintel, and the system was first integrated in 1958.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] BAE Systems, as the successor to Elliotts via GEC-Marconi Avionics, thus has a claim to the world's first head-up display in operational service.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] A similar version that replaced the bombing modes with missile-attack modes was part of the AIRPASS HUD fitted to the English Electric Lightning from 1959.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] In the United Kingdom, it was soon noted that pilots flying with the new gunsights were becoming better at piloting their aircraft.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] At this point, the HUD expanded its purpose beyond weapon aiming to general piloting.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] In the 1960s, French test-pilot Gilbert Klopfstein created the first modern HUD and a standardized system of HUD symbols so that pilots would only have to learn one system and could more easily transition between aircraft.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] The modern HUD used in instrument flight rules approaches to landing was developed in 1975.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] Klopfstein pioneered HUD technology in military fighter jets and helicopters, aiming to centralize critical flight data within the pilot's field of vision.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] This approach sought to increase the pilot's scan efficiency and reduce "task saturation" and information overload.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] Use of HUDs then expanded beyond military aircraft.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] In the 1970s, the HUD was introduced to commercial aviation, and in 1988, the Oldsmobile Cutlass Supreme became the first production car with a head-up display.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] Until a few years ago, the Embraer 190, Saab 2000, Boeing 727, and Boeing 737 Classic (737-300/400/500) and Next Generation aircraft (737-600/700/800/900 series) were the only commercial passenger aircraft available with HUDs.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] However, the technology is becoming more common with aircraft such as the Canadair RJ, Airbus A318 and several business jets featuring the displays.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] HUDs have become standard equipment on the Boeing 787.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] Furthermore, the Airbus A320, A330, A340 and A380 families are currently undergoing the certification process for a HUD.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] HUDs were also added to the Space Shuttle orbiter.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] On aircraft avionics systems, HUDs typically operate from dual independent redundant computer systems.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] They receive input directly from the sensors (pitot-static, gyroscopic, navigation, etc.) aboard the aircraft and perform their own computations rather than receiving previously computed data from the flight computers.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] On other aircraft (the Boeing 787, for example) the HUD guidance computation for Low Visibility Take-off (LVTO) and low visibility approach comes from the same flight guidance computer that drives the autopilot.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] Computers are integrated with the aircraft's systems and allow connectivity onto several different data buses such as the ARINC 429, ARINC 629, and MIL-STD-1553.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] Typical aircraft HUDs display airspeed, altitude, a horizon line, heading, turn/bank and slip/skid indicators.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] These instruments are the minimum required by 14 CFR Part 91.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] Keeping the FPV on the horizon allows the pilot to fly level turns in various angles of bank.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] During the 1980s, the United States military tested the use of HUDs in vertical take off and landing (VTOL) and short take off and landing (STOL) aircraft.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] A HUD format was developed at NASA Ames Research Center to provide pilots of VTOL and STOL aircraft with complete flight guidance and control information for Category III C terminal-area flight operations.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] This includes a large variety of flight operations, from STOL flights on land-based runways to VTOL operations on aircraft carriers.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] The principal features of this display format are the integration of the flightpath and pursuit guidance information into a narrow field of view, easily assimilated by the pilot with a single glance, and the superposition of vertical and horizontal situation information.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] The display is a derivative of a successful design developed for conventional transport aircraft.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] The use of head-up displays allows commercial aircraft substantial flexibility in their operations.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] Systems have been approved which allow reduced-visibility takeoffs, and landings, as well as full manual Category III A landings and roll-outs.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] Initially expensive and physically large, these systems were only installed on larger aircraft able to support them.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] These tended to be the same aircraft that as standard supported autoland (with the exception of certain turbo-prop types that had HUD as an option) making the head-up display unnecessary for Cat III landings.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] This delayed the adoption of HUD in commercial aircraft.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] At the same time, studies have shown that the use of a HUD during landings decreases the lateral deviation from centerline in all landing conditions, although the touchdown point along the centerline is not changed.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] Flight data from a tablet computer can be projected on the $1,800 Epic Optix Eagle 1 HUD.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] In more advanced systems, such as the US Federal Aviation Administration (FAA)-labeled 'Enhanced Flight Vision System', a real-world visual image can be overlaid onto the combiner.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] Typically an infrared camera (either single or multi-band) is installed in the nose of the aircraft to display a conformed image to the pilot.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] When used with a HUD however, the camera must be mounted as close as possible to the pilots eye point as the image is expected to "overlay" the real world as the pilot looks through the combiner.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] "Registration", or the accurate overlay of the EVS image with the real world image, is one feature closely examined by authorities prior to approval of a HUD based EVS.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] This is because of the importance of the HUD matching the real world and therefore being able to provide accurate data rather than misleading information.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] While the EVS display can greatly help, the FAA has only relaxed operating regulations so an aircraft with EVS can perform a CATEGORY I approach to CATEGORY II minimums.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] In all other cases the flight crew must comply with all "unaided" visual restrictions.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] HUD systems are also being designed to display a synthetic vision system (SVS) graphic image, which uses high precision navigation, attitude, altitude and terrain databases to create realistic and intuitive views of the outside world.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] In the 1st SVS head down image shown on the right, immediately visible indicators include the airspeed tape on the left, altitude tape on the right, and turn/bank/slip/skid displays at the top center.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] Unlike this color depiction of SVS on a head down primary flight display, the SVS displayed on a HUD is monochrome – that is, typically, in shades of green.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] This is the guidance cue coming from the Flight Guidance System.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] When stabilized on the approach, this purple symbol should be centered *within* the FPV.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] The terrain is entirely computer generated from a high resolution terrain database.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] In some systems, the SVS will calculate the aircraft's current flight path, or possible flight path (based on an aircraft performance model, the aircraft's current energy, and surrounding terrain) and then turn any obstructions red to alert the flight crew.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] Such a system might have helped prevent the crash of American Airlines Flight 965 into a mountain in December 1995.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] On the left side of the display is an SVS-unique symbol, with the appearance of a purple, diminishing sideways ladder, and which continues on the right of the display.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] The two lines define a "tunnel in the sky".
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] This symbol defines the desired trajectory of the aircraft in three dimensions.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] For example, if the pilot had selected an airport to the left, then this symbol would curve off to the left and down.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] If the pilot keeps the flight path vector alongside the trajectory symbol, the craft will fly the optimum path.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] This path would be based on information stored in the Flight Management System's database and would show the FAA-approved approach for that airport.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] In mid-2017, the Israel Defense Forces will begin trials of Elbit's Iron Vision, the world's first helmet-mounted head-up display for tanks.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] Israel's Elbit, which developed the helmet-mounted display system for the F-35, plans Iron Vision to use a number of externally mounted cameras to project the 360° view of a tank's surroundings onto the helmet-mounted visors of its crew members.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] This allows the crew members to stay inside the tank, without having to open the hatches to see outside.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] A program announced in 2025 by a collaboration of Patria Technologies and Distance Technologies aims to place the head-up display on the windshield of vehicles, so as to not require a helmet.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] The program also intends on using AI to aid in data display and processing.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] These displays are becoming increasingly available in production cars, and usually offer speedometer, tachometer, and navigation system displays.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] Night vision information is also displayed via HUD on certain automobiles.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] In contrast to most HUDs found in aircraft, automotive head-up displays are not parallax-free.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] The display may not be visible to a driver wearing sunglasses with polarised lenses.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] Add-on HUD systems also exist, projecting the display onto a glass combiner mounted above or below the windshield, or using the windshield itself as the combiner.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] The first in-car HUD was developed by General Motors Corporation in 1999 with the function of displaying the navigation service in front of the driver's line of sight.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] Moving into 2010, AR technology was introduced and combined with the existing in-car HUD.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] Based on this technology, the navigation service began to be displayed on the windshield of the vehicle.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] Motorcycle helmet HUDs are also commercially available.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] Mercedes Benz introduced an Augmented Reality-based Head Up Display while Faurecia invested in an eye gaze and finger controlled head up display.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] HUDs have been proposed or are being experimentally developed for a number of other applications.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] In military settings, a HUD can be used to overlay tactical information such as the output of a laser rangefinder or squadmate locations to infantrymen.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] A prototype HUD has also been developed that displays information on the inside of a swimmer's goggles or of a scuba diver's mask.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] HUD systems that project information directly onto the wearer's retina with a low-powered laser (virtual retinal display) are also being tested.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] A HUD product developed in 2012 could perform real-time language translation.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] In an implementation of an Optical head-mounted display, the EyeTap product allows superimposed computer-generated graphic files to be displayed on a lens.
[src:avionics-systems/head-up-display] The Google Glass was another early product.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Often the inertial sensors are supplemented by a barometric altimeter and sometimes by magnetic sensors (magnetometers) and/or speed measuring devices.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] INSs are used on mobile robots and on vehicles such as ships, aircraft, submarines, guided missiles, and spacecraft.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Older INS systems generally used an inertial platform as their mounting point to the vehicle and the terms are sometimes considered synonymous.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Inertial navigation is a self-contained navigation technique in which measurements provided by accelerometers and gyroscopes are used to track the position and orientation of an object relative to a known starting point, orientation and velocity.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Inertial measurement units (IMUs) typically contain three orthogonal rate-gyroscopes and three orthogonal accelerometers, measuring angular velocity and linear acceleration respectively.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] By processing signals from these devices it is possible to track the position and orientation of a device.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] An inertial navigation system includes at least a computer and a platform or module containing accelerometers, gyroscopes, or other motion-sensing devices.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] The INS is initially provided with its position and velocity from another source (a human operator, a GPS satellite receiver, etc.) accompanied with the initial orientation and thereafter computes its own updated position and velocity by integrating information received from the motion sensors.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] The advantage of an INS is that it requires no external references in order to determine its position, orientation, or velocity once it has been initialized.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] An INS can detect a change in its geographic position (a move east or north, for example), a change in its velocity (speed and direction of movement) and a change in its orientation (rotation about an axis).
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] It does this by measuring the linear acceleration and angular velocity applied to the system.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Since it requires no external reference (after initialization), it is immune to jamming and deception.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Gyroscopes measure the angular displacement of the sensor frame with respect to the inertial reference frame.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] By using the original orientation of the system in the inertial reference frame as the initial condition and integrating the angular displacement, the system's current orientation is known at all times.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] This can be thought of as the ability of a blindfolded passenger in a car to feel the car turn left and right or tilt up and down as the car ascends or descends hills.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Based on this information alone, the passenger knows what direction the car is facing, but not how fast or slow it is moving, or whether it is sliding sideways.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Accelerometers measure the linear acceleration of the moving vehicle in the sensor or body frame, but in directions that can only be measured relative to the moving system (since the accelerometers are fixed to the system and rotate with the system, but are not aware of their own orientation).
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] However, by tracking both the current angular velocity of the system and the current linear acceleration of the system measured relative to the moving system, it is possible to determine the linear acceleration of the system in the inertial reference frame.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Performing integration on the inertial accelerations (using the original velocity as the initial conditions) using the correct kinematic equations yields the inertial velocities of the system and integration again (using the original position as the initial condition) yields the inertial position.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Inertial navigation is used in a wide range of applications including the navigation of aircraft, tactical and strategic missiles, spacecraft, submarines and ships.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] It is also embedded in some mobile phones for purposes of mobile phone location and tracking.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Recent advances in the construction of microelectromechanical systems (MEMS) have made it possible to manufacture small and light inertial navigation systems.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] These advances have widened the range of possible applications to include areas such as human and animal motion capture.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Inertial navigation systems are used in many different moving objects.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] However, their cost and complexity place constraints on the environments in which they are practical for use.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] To support the use of inertial technology in the best way, already in 1965 a technical working group for Inertial Sensors had been established in Germany to bring together the users, the manufacturers and the researchers of inertial sensors.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] This working group has been continuously developed and today it is known as DGON ISA Inertial Sensors and Application Symposium, the leading conference for inertial technologies for more than 60 years.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] This Symposium DGON / IEEE ISA with about 200 international attendees is held annually in October in Germany.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] The publications of all DGON ISA conferences over the last more than 60 years are accessible.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] All inertial navigation systems suffer from integration drift: small errors in the measurement of acceleration and angular velocity are integrated into progressively larger errors in velocity, which are compounded into still greater errors in position.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Since the new position is calculated from the previous calculated position and the measured acceleration and angular velocity, these errors accumulate roughly proportionally to the time since the initial position was input.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Even the best accelerometers, with a standard error of 10 micro-g, would accumulate a 50-meter (164-ft) error within 17 minutes.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Therefore, the position must be periodically corrected by input from some other type of navigation system.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Accordingly, inertial navigation is usually used to supplement other navigation systems, providing a higher degree of accuracy than is possible with the use of any single system.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] For example, if, in terrestrial use, the inertially tracked velocity is intermittently updated to zero by stopping, the position will remain precise for a much longer time, a so-called *zero velocity update*.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] In aerospace particularly, other measurement systems are used to determine INS inaccuracies, e.g. the Honeywell LaseRefV inertial navigation systems uses GPS and air data computer outputs to maintain required navigation performance.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] The navigation error rises with the lower sensitivity of the sensors used.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Currently, devices combining different sensors are being developed, e.g. attitude and heading reference system.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Because the navigation error is mainly influenced by the numerical integration of angular rates and accelerations, the pressure reference system was developed to use one numerical integration of the angular rate measurements.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Estimation theory in general and Kalman filtering in particular, provide a theoretical framework for combining information from various sensors.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] One of the most common alternative sensors is a satellite navigation radio such as GPS, which can be used for all kinds of vehicles with direct sky visibility.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Indoor applications can use pedometers, distance measurement equipment, or other kinds of position sensors.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] By properly combining the information from an INS and other systems (GPS), the errors in position and velocity are stable.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Furthermore, INS can be used as a short-term fallback while GPS signals are unavailable, for example when a vehicle passes through a tunnel.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] In 2011, GPS jamming at the civilian level became a governmental concern.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] The relative ease in ability to jam these systems has motivated the military to reduce navigation dependence on GPS technology.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Because inertial navigation sensors do not depend on radio signals unlike GPS, they cannot be jammed.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Army Research Laboratory reported a method to merge measurements from 10 pairs of MEMS gyroscope and accelerometers (plus occasional GPS), reducing the positional error by two thirds for a projectile.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] The algorithm can correct for systemic biases in individual sensors, using both GPS and a heuristic based on the gun-firing acceleration force.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] If one sensor consistently over or underestimates distance, the system can adjust the corrupted sensor's contributions to the final calculation.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Inertial navigation systems were originally developed for rockets.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] American rocketry pioneer Robert Goddard experimented with rudimentary gyroscopic systems.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Goddard's systems were of great interest to contemporary German pioneers including Wernher von Braun.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] The systems entered more widespread use with the advent of spacecraft, guided missiles, and commercial airliners.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Early German World War II V2 guidance systems combined two gyroscopes and a lateral accelerometer with a simple analog computer to adjust the azimuth for the rocket in flight.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Analog computer signals were used to drive four graphite rudders in the rocket exhaust for flight control.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] The GN&C (Guidance, Navigation, and Control) system for the V2 provided many innovations as an integrated platform with closed loop guidance.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] At the end of the war von Braun engineered the surrender of 500 of his top rocket scientists, along with plans and test vehicles, to the Americans.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] They arrived at Fort Bliss, Texas in 1945 under the provisions of Operation Paperclip and were subsequently moved to Huntsville, Alabama, in 1950 where they worked for U.S.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] In the early 1950s, the US government wanted to insulate itself against over-dependency on the German team for military applications, including the development of a fully domestic missile guidance program.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] The technical monitor for the MIT task was engineer Jim Fletcher, who later served as NASA Administrator.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] The Atlas guidance system was to be a combination of an on-board autonomous system and a ground-based tracking and command system.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] The self-contained system finally prevailed in ballistic missile applications for obvious reasons.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] In space exploration, a mixture of the two remains.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Halcombe "Hal" Laning, Jr., researched computational based solutions to guidance and undertook the initial analytical work on the Atlas inertial guidance in 1954.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Other key figures at Convair were Charlie Bossart, the Chief Engineer, and Walter Schweidetzky, head of the guidance group.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Schweidetzky had worked with von Braun at Peenemünde during World War II.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] The initial Delta guidance system assessed the difference in position from a reference trajectory.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] A velocity to be gained (VGO) calculation is made to correct the current trajectory with the objective of driving VGO to zero.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] The mathematics of this approach were fundamentally valid, but dropped because of the challenges in accurate inertial guidance and analog computing power.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] The challenges faced by the Delta efforts were overcome by the Q system (see Q-guidance) of guidance.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] The Q system's revolution was to bind the challenges of missile guidance (and associated equations of motion) in the matrix Q.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] The Q matrix represents the partial derivatives of the velocity with respect to the position vector.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] A key feature of this approach allowed for the components of the vector cross product (v, xdv, /dt) to be used as the basic autopilot rate signals—a technique that became known as *cross-product steering*.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] The Q-system was presented at the first Technical Symposium on Ballistic Missiles held at the Ramo-Wooldridge Corporation in Los Angeles on 21 and 22 June 1956.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] The Q system was classified information through the 1960s.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Derivations of this guidance are used for today's missiles.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] In February 1961 NASA awarded MIT a contract for preliminary design study of a guidance and navigation system for the Apollo program.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] MIT and the Delco Electronics Div. of General Motors Corp. were awarded the joint contract for design and production of the Apollo Guidance and Navigation systems for the Command Module and the Lunar Module.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Delco produced the IMUs (Inertial Measurement Units) for these systems, Kollsman Instrument Corp. produced the Optical Systems, and the Apollo Guidance Computer was built by Raytheon under subcontract.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] For the Space Shuttle, open loop guidance was used to guide the Shuttle from lift-off until Solid Rocket Booster (SRB) separation.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] After SRB separation the primary Space Shuttle guidance is named PEG (Powered Explicit Guidance).
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] PEG takes into account both the Q system and the predictor-corrector attributes of the original "Delta" System (PEG Guidance).
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Although many updates to the Shuttle's navigation system had taken place over the last 30 years (ex.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] GPS in the OI-22 build), the guidance core of the Shuttle GN&C system had evolved little.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Within a crewed system, there is a human interface needed for the guidance system.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] As astronauts are the customer for the system, many new teams were formed that touch GN&C as it is a primary interface to "fly" the vehicle.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] One example of a popular INS for commercial aircraft was the Delco Carousel, which provided partial automation of navigation in the days before complete flight management systems became commonplace.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] The Carousel allowed pilots to enter 9 waypoints at a time and then guided the aircraft from one waypoint to the next using an INS to determine aircraft position and velocity.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Boeing Corporation subcontracted the Delco Electronics Div. of General Motors to design and build the first production Carousel systems for the early models (-100, -200 and -300) of the 747 aircraft.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] The 747 utilized three Carousel systems operating in concert for reliability purposes.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] The Carousel system and derivatives thereof were subsequently adopted for use in many other commercial and military aircraft.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] The USAF C-141 was the first military aircraft to utilize the Carousel in a dual system configuration, followed by the C-5A which utilized the triple INS configuration, similar to the 747.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] The KC-135A fleet was fitted with a single Carousel IV-E system that could operate as a stand-alone INS or can be aided by the AN/APN-81 or AN/APN-218 Doppler radar.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Some special-mission variants of the C-135 were fitted with dual Carousel IV-E INSs.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] ARINC Characteristic 704 defines the INS used in commercial air transport.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] INSs contain Inertial Measurement Units (IMUs) which have angular and linear accelerometers (for changes in position); some IMUs include a gyroscopic element (for maintaining an absolute angular reference).
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Angular accelerometers measure how the vehicle is rotating in space.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Generally, there is at least one sensor for each of the three axes: pitch (nose up and down), yaw (nose left and right) and roll (clockwise or counter-clockwise from the cockpit).
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Linear accelerometers measure non-gravitational accelerations of the vehicle.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Since it can move in three axes (up and down, left and right, forward and back), there is a linear accelerometer for each axis.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] A computer continually calculates the vehicle's current position.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] First, for each of the six degrees of freedom (x,y,z and θx, θy and θz), it integrates over time the sensed acceleration, together with an estimate of gravity, to calculate the current velocity.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Then it integrates the velocity to calculate the current position.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Inertial guidance is difficult without computers.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] The desire to use inertial guidance in the Minuteman missile and Project Apollo drove early attempts to miniaturize computers.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Inertial guidance systems are now usually combined with satellite navigation systems through a digital filtering system.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] The inertial system provides short term data, while the satellite system corrects accumulated errors of the inertial system.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] An inertial guidance system that will operate near the surface of the earth must incorporate Schuler tuning so that its platform will continue pointing towards the center of the Earth as a vehicle moves from place to place.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Some systems place the linear accelerometers on a gimballed gyrostabilized platform.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] The gimbals are a set of three rings, each with a pair of bearings initially at right angles.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] They let the platform twist about any rotational axis (or, rather, they let the platform keep the same orientation while the vehicle rotates around it).
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] There are two gyroscopes (usually) on the platform.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Two gyroscopes are used to cancel gyroscopic precession, the tendency of a gyroscope to twist at right angles to an input torque.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] By mounting a pair of gyroscopes (of the same rotational inertia and spinning at the same speed in opposite directions) at right angles the precessions are cancelled and the platform will resist twisting.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] This system allows a vehicle's roll, pitch and yaw angles to be measured directly at the bearings of the gimbals.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Relatively simple electronic circuits can be used to add up the linear accelerations, because the directions of the linear accelerometers do not change.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] The big disadvantage of this scheme is that it uses many expensive precision mechanical parts.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] It also has moving parts that can wear out or jam and is vulnerable to gimbal lock.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] The primary guidance system of the Apollo spacecraft used a three-axis gyrostabilized platform, feeding data to the Apollo Guidance Computer.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Maneuvers had to be carefully planned to avoid gimbal lock.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Gimbal lock constrains maneuvering and it would be beneficial to eliminate the slip rings and bearings of the gimbals.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Therefore, some systems use fluid bearings or a flotation chamber to mount a gyrostabilized platform.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] These systems can have very high precisions (e.g., Advanced Inertial Reference Sphere).
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Like all gyrostabilized platforms, this system runs well with relatively slow, low-power computers.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] The fluid bearings are pads with holes through which pressurized inert gas (such as helium) or oil presses against the spherical shell of the platform.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] The fluid bearings are very slippery and the spherical platform can turn freely.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] There are usually four bearing pads, mounted in a tetrahedral arrangement to support the platform.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] In premium systems, the angular sensors are usually specialized transformer coils made in a strip on a flexible printed circuit board.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Several coil strips are mounted on great circles around the spherical shell of the gyrostabilized platform.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Electronics outside the platform uses similar strip-shaped transformers to read the varying magnetic fields produced by the transformers wrapped around the spherical platform.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Whenever a magnetic field changes shape, or moves, it will cut the wires of the coils on the external transformer strips.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] The cutting generates an electric current in the external strip-shaped coils and electronics can measure that current to derive angles.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Cheap systems sometimes use bar codes to sense orientations and use solar cells or a single transformer to power the platform.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Some small missiles have powered the platform with light from a window or optic fibers to the motor.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] A research topic is to suspend the platform with pressure from exhaust gases.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Data is returned to the outside world via the transformers, or sometimes LEDs communicating with external photodiodes.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Lightweight digital computers permit the system to eliminate the gimbals, creating *strapdown* systems, so called because their sensors are simply strapped to the vehicle.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] This reduces the cost, eliminates gimbal lock, removes the need for some calibrations and increases the reliability by eliminating some of the moving parts.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Angular rate sensors called *rate gyros* measure the angular velocity of the vehicle.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] A strapdown system needs a dynamic measurement range several hundred times that required by a gimballed system.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] That is, it must integrate the vehicle's attitude changes in pitch, roll and yaw, as well as gross movements.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Gimballed systems could usually do well with update rates of 50–60 Hz.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] However, strapdown systems normally update about 2000 Hz.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] The higher rate is needed to let the navigation system integrate the angular rate into an attitude accurately.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] The data updating algorithms (*direction cosines* or quaternions) involved are too complex to be accurately performed except by digital electronics.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] However, digital computers are now so inexpensive and fast that rate gyro systems can now be practically used and mass-produced.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] The Apollo lunar module used a strapdown system in its backup Abort Guidance System (AGS).
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Strapdown systems are nowadays commonly used in commercial and military applications (aircraft, ships, ROVs, missiles, etc.).
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] State-of-the-art strapdown systems are based upon ring laser gyroscopes, fibre optic gyrocopes or hemispherical resonator gyroscopes.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] They are using digital electronics and advanced digital filtering techniques such as Kalman filter.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] The orientation of a gyroscope system can sometimes also be inferred simply from its position history (e.g., GPS).
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] This is, in particular, the case with planes and cars, where the velocity vector usually implies the orientation of the vehicle body.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] For example, Honeywell's *Align in Motion* is an initialization process where the initialization occurs while the aircraft is moving, in the air or on the ground.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] This is accomplished using GPS and an inertial reasonableness test, thereby allowing commercial data integrity requirements to be met.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] This process has been FAA certified to recover pure INS performance equivalent to stationary alignment procedures for civilian flight times up to 18 hours.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] It avoids the need for gyroscope batteries on aircraft.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Less-expensive navigation systems, intended for use in automobiles, may use a vibrating structure gyroscope to detect changes in heading and the odometer pickup to measure distance covered along the vehicle's track.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] This type of system is much less accurate than a higher-end INS, but it is adequate for the typical automobile application where GPS is the primary navigation system and dead reckoning is only needed to fill gaps in GPS coverage when buildings or terrain block the satellite signals.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] If a standing wave is induced in a hemispheric resonant structure and then the resonant structure is rotated, the spherical harmonic standing wave rotates through an angle different from the quartz resonator structure due to the Coriolis force.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] The movement of the outer case with respect to the standing wave pattern is proportional to the total rotation angle and can be sensed by appropriate electronics.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] The system resonators are machined from fused quartz due to its excellent mechanical properties.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] The electrodes that drive and sense the standing waves are deposited directly onto separate quartz structures that surround the resonator.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] These gyros can operate in either a whole angle mode (which gives them nearly unlimited rate capability) or a force rebalance mode that holds the standing wave in a fixed orientation with respect to the gyro housing (which gives them much better accuracy).
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] This system has almost no moving parts and is very accurate.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] However it is still relatively expensive due to the cost of the precision ground and polished hollow quartz hemispheres.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Northrop Grumman currently manufactures IMUs (inertial measurement units) for spacecraft that use HRGs.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] These IMUs have demonstrated extremely high reliability since their initial use in 1996.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Safran manufactures large numbers of HRG based inertial navigation systems dedicated to a wide range of applications.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] These products include "tuning fork gyros".
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Here, the gyro is designed as an electronically driven tuning fork, often fabricated out of a single piece of quartz or silicon.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Such gyros operate in accordance with the dynamic theory that when an angle rate is applied to a translating body, a Coriolis force is generated.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] This system is usually integrated on a silicon chip.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] It has two mass-balanced quartz tuning forks, arranged "handle-to-handle" so forces cancel.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Aluminum electrodes evaporated onto the forks and the underlying chip both drive and sense the motion.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] The system is both manufacturable and inexpensive.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Since quartz is dimensionally stable, the system can be accurate.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] As the forks are twisted about the axis of the handle, the vibration of the tines tends to continue in the same plane of motion.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] This motion has to be resisted by electrostatic forces from the electrodes under the tines.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] By measuring the difference in capacitance between the two tines of a fork, the system can determine the rate of angular motion.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Current state-of-the-art non-military technology (as of 2005) can build small solid-state sensors that can measure human body movements.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] These devices have no moving parts and weigh about 50 grams (2 ounces).
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Solid-state devices using the same physical principles are used for image stabilization in small cameras or camcorders.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] These can be extremely small, around 5 millimetres (0.20 inches) and are built with microelectromechanical systems (MEMS) technologies.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Sensors based on magnetohydrodynamic principles can be used to measure angular velocities.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] MEMS gyroscopes typically rely on the Coriolis effect to measure angular velocity.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] It consists of a resonating proof mass mounted in silicon.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] The gyroscope is, unlike an accelerometer, an active sensor.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] The proof mass is pushed back and forth by driving combs.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] A rotation of the gyroscope generates a Coriolis force that is acting on the mass which results in a motion in a different direction.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] The motion in this direction is measured by electrodes and represents the rate of turn.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] A ring laser gyro (RLG) splits a beam of laser light into two beams in opposite directions through narrow tunnels in a closed circular optical path around the perimeter of a triangular block of temperature-stable Cervit glass with reflecting mirrors placed in each corner.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] When the gyro is rotating at some angular rate, the distance traveled by each beam will differ—the shorter path being opposite to the rotation.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] The phase shift between the two beams can be measured by an interferometer and is proportional to the rate of rotation (Sagnac effect).
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] In practice, at low rotation rates the output frequency can drop to zero as the result of backscattering causing the beams to synchronise and lock together.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] This is known as a *lock-in*, or *laser-lock*.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] The result is that there is no change in the interference pattern and therefore no measurement change.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] The shaker is the most accurate, because both light beams use exactly the same path.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Thus laser gyros retain moving parts, but they do not move as far.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] The basic mechanism, monochromatic laser light travelling in opposite paths and the Sagnac effect, is the same in a FOG and a RLG, but the engineering details are substantially different in the FOG compared to earlier laser gyros.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Precise winding of the fiber-optic coil is required to ensure the paths taken by the light in opposite directions are as similar as possible.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] The FOG requires more complex calibrations than a laser ring gyro making the development and manufacture of FOG's more technically challenging that for a RLG.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] However FOG's do not suffer from laser lock at low speeds and do not need to contain any moving parts, increasing the maximum potential accuracy and lifespan of a FOG over an equivalent RLG.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] The basic, open-loop accelerometer consists of a mass attached to a spring.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] The mass is constrained to move only in line with the spring.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Acceleration causes deflection of the mass and the offset distance is measured.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] The acceleration is derived from the values of deflection distance, mass and the spring constant.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] The system must also be damped to avoid oscillation.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] A closed-loop accelerometer achieves higher performance by using a feedback loop to cancel the deflection, thus keeping the mass nearly stationary.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Whenever the mass deflects, the feedback loop causes an electric coil to apply an equally negative force on the mass, canceling the motion.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Acceleration is derived from the amount of negative force applied.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Because the mass barely moves, the effects of non-linearities of the spring and damping system are greatly reduced.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] In addition, this accelerometer provides for increased bandwidth beyond the natural frequency of the sensing element.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Both types of accelerometers have been manufactured as integrated micro-machinery on silicon chips.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] DARPA's Microsystems Technology Office (MTO) department is working on a Micro-PNT (Micro-Technology for Positioning, Navigation and Timing) program to design Timing & Inertial Measurement Unit (TIMU) chips that do absolute position tracking on a single chip without GPS-aided navigation.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Micro-PNT adds a highly accurate master timing clock integrated into an IMU (Inertial Measurement Unit) chip, making it a Timing & Inertial Measurement Unit chip.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] A TIMU chip integrates 3-axis gyroscope, 3-axis accelerometer and 3-axis magnetometer together with a highly accurate master timing clock, so that it can simultaneously measure the motion tracked and combine that with timing from the synchronized clock.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] In one form, the navigational system of equations acquires linear and angular measurements from the inertial and body frame, respectively and calculates the final attitude and position in the NED frame of reference.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Where f is specific force, $\omega$ is angular rate, a is acceleration, R is position, ${\dot {R}}$ and V are velocity, $\Omega$ is the angular velocity of the earth, g is the acceleration due to gravity, $\Phi ,\lambda$ and h are the NED location parameters.
[src:avionics-systems/inertial-navigation-system] Also, super/subscripts of E, I and B are representing variables in the Earth centered, inertial or body reference frame, respectively and C is a transformation of reference frames.
